00:06:04.399 --> 00:06:10.640
from Edwards and McGee, and then you start looking for the telltale patterns. What patterns, exactly?

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:14.799
Well, it turns out there are a lot. Some of them seem more or less unobjectionable.

00:06:15.519 --> 00:06:22.160
A number will go up, a number will go down, a number will go sideways. I think this style of drawing is very

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:26.399
nice, by the way. They're not like sparklines, right, that people put in summary tables even today.

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:30.799
But the chart men also thought that you should take care to look at fluctuations within the trend.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:36.320
They were very keen to argue that downward trends, true downward trends, had to be measured by the

00:06:36.320 --> 00:06:41.839
downward trends of the highs, whereas true upward trends had to be measured by the upward tendencies

00:06:41.839 --> 00:06:48.000
of the lows, for example. Now anyone can see a basic upward or downward trend, but at this point

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.679
the theory starts to get a little richer. One idea was that after a period of steady growth, you would

00:06:53.679 --> 00:06:58.239
