to making our work more trustworthy? After all, when someone tells you a story, when someone

00:19:00.319 --> 00:19:04.640
shows you a graph and gives you an interpretation of it, you want to know whether you can believe

00:19:04.640 --> 00:19:10.400
them, whether you can trust it. Here's why I think this is worth emphasizing. I think that whatever

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:14.560
it is that makes a data visualization trustworthy, it isn't really something you can include in the

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:20.079
graph. If you look at stock examples of bad graphs, especially older ones, it's kind of comforting

00:19:20.079 --> 00:19:25.119
because most of them look really janky. And the same goes for contemporary examples of bad

00:19:25.119 --> 00:19:30.000
marketing materials or from media outlets trying to spin some ridiculous visual summary of polling

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:37.119
data. They don't look trustworthy. It's possible to make janky graphs with ggplot, but you kind of

00:19:37.119 --> 00:19:43.280
have to work at it. By default, ggplot makes a lot of good choices for you, and this gives it what

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:48.319
you might call a kind of aura of plausibility. Whatever data you're showing and whatever story

00:19:48.319 --> 00:19:53.599
you're telling benefits from a kind of rhetoric of credibility that's built into the software,

00:19:53.599 --> 00:19:58.000
more or less out of the box. With just a little bit of extra work, you can polish up your dot plot

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:04.239
to make a poster, or if it's your job, you can make an effective visual argument into financial

00:20:04.239 --> 00:20:08.800
times like John Byrne Murdoch does there, or a beautiful, well-thought-out contribution to

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:14.079
Tidy Tuesday like Cedric Shearer does in the bottom right corner there. So what does that mean

00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:20.319
to trust a visualization? As you might expect, there are large social scientific and philosophical

00:20:20.319 --> 00:20:24.959
literatures about trustworthiness. And like in many social scientific literatures, if you read them,

00:20:24.959 --> 00:20:29.520
you find that empirical studies confirm that trust has many dimensions. It's also really quite

00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:34.719
hard to measure, and it's very complicated. And like in many philosophical literatures, if you

00:20:34.719 --> 00:20:39.119
read them, it turns out that trust has many senses, and it's really quite hard to give a unified

00:20:39.119 --> 00:20:44.400
account of, and it's very complicated. Ever since the work of Annette Byer, the philosophical

00:20:44.400 --> 00:20:48.160
literature has made this distinction between trust and what gets called mere reliability.

00:20:48.719 --> 00:20:52.239
Now, in ordinary speech, trust can mean reliability too, but the idea is that our

00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:57.280
everyday way of talking is fairly loose, and it runs together something that's worth making a

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:00.319
distinction about. And the argument is roughly that there are a lot of things in people that

00:21:00.319 --> 00:21:05.040
we rely on without actually trusting them. In particular, if they failed, we wouldn't say

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:08.800
that we expected an apology from them. We wouldn't feel betrayed. We wouldn't feel that we'd been

00:21:08.800 --> 00:21:14.719
lied to. So for example, I might rely on you having a USB cable I can borrow in an emergency

00:21:14.719 --> 00:21:18.400
if I want to give a presentation, because I know you're the kind of person, I know you're out there,

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:23.040
who has a bag full of cables from all kinds of things, and you've always had one before when I've

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:28.800
asked to borrow one. But if I needed one and you happened not to have your bag with you one day,

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:34.800
I couldn't reasonably say that you had betrayed my trust. Or I might rely on my alarm clock to

00:21:34.800 --> 00:21:38.319
wake me up, but if it failed one morning, I'd be making a kind of mistake if I thought that

00:21:38.319 --> 00:21:43.520
it owed me an apology. Another philosopher, Catherine Hawley, argues that trusting someone

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:47.040
to do something means, first of all, believing that they have a commitment to doing a thing,

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:51.520
and then relying on them to meet that commitment. A trustworthy person keeps their commitments.

00:21:52.319 --> 00:21:55.839
And when you mistrust someone, it's because you think they have a commitment to something,

00:21:55.839 --> 00:22:00.640
but you doubt that they can be relied on to meet it. What's interesting about Hawley's view,

00:22:00.640 --> 00:22:06.000
amongst other things, is the negative implications of that. Because being trustworthy, for her,

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:12.000
is mostly about making sure you don't end up getting stuck with commitments that you can't,

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:18.319
won't, or don't fulfill. Being trustworthy doesn't mean taking on as many commitments as

00:22:18.319 --> 00:22:23.520
you possibly can. Being trustworthy doesn't mean that you have an obligation to be responsive to

00:22:23.520 --> 00:22:29.439
every single demand made of you. Being trustworthy doesn't mean that you're answerable to literally

00:22:29.439 --> 00:22:34.000
anyone. Now, in a talk like this, I can't give these ideas the room they deserve, but they're

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:39.280
useful when we think about what we're looking at when we're looking at data and we're showing

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:45.839
visualizations. Because even in quite technical discussions, I find that

00:22:47.359 --> 00:22:50.239
when we're talking about how we should proceed or what should we do,

00:22:51.599 --> 00:22:55.359
again, even in quite technical discussions, the topic moves very quickly to issues of

00:22:55.920 --> 00:23:00.640
social relations, of people's roles, and the expectations associated with these roles,

00:23:00.640 --> 00:23:04.560
what we can reasonably expect. Not so much the technical issues, but sort of the context in

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:09.119
which they're embedded and whether we can, you know, what should we expect of others and what

00:23:09.119 --> 00:23:13.520
are the limits on those expectations? And this is a general feature of any kind of organized

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:18.160
knowledge production. Data visualization is a good case because a graph is such a deceptively

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:23.599
simple and portable object. When you make a graph and tell a story with it, all kinds of norms and

00:23:23.599 --> 00:23:28.800
expectations get compacted down into this single thing, into an image meant to authoritatively

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:32.640
convey some structured bit of information to somebody. And when you tell a story with your

00:23:32.640 --> 00:23:36.800
data, you're implicitly warranting it. You're making some commitments. You're not offering an

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:41.119
unconditional warranty. You're not beholden to everyone for all time. But questions of trust do

00:23:41.119 --> 00:23:46.000
arise. So when you look at this modern classic of data visualization, for example, what I made,

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:51.599
you might ask yourself, can I trust this? Does it look like the person who made this knows what

00:23:51.599 --> 00:23:56.319
they're doing? And if you spent any time looking at graphs, then you know the answer is absolutely

00:23:56.319 --> 00:24:02.560
not, which is too bad. I mean, look at these beautiful drop shadows, that finely textured

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:10.880
wood grain, the tasteful use of papyrus, the king of off-brand herbal tea fonts. What could be more

00:24:10.880 --> 00:24:16.719
warmly authentic? No. As a seasoned consumer of visualizations, you know that you're better off

00:24:16.719 --> 00:24:20.800
relying on something more like this, something with a higher data-to-ink ratio, as Edward Tufty

00:24:20.800 --> 00:24:24.000
would say, although you might also think we could do a little better, maybe something like this.

00:24:24.800 --> 00:24:29.199
This is a Cleveland dot plot. Here, the x-axis doesn't go to zero, just covers the range of

00:24:29.199 --> 00:24:33.760
the data. That's ggplot's default behavior, and it's the default behavior in most modern

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:39.760
visualization toolkits. By the way, here's some advice. Any graph with a categorical axis

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:45.599
and a continuous axis is really a kind of table in disguise. So put your categories on the y-axis,

00:24:45.599 --> 00:24:50.079
that is, in the rows, and the continuous value on the x-axis. No more faffing about trying to

00:24:50.079 --> 00:24:55.040
rotate your text or your head. For many audiences, a graph like this is perfectly fine,

00:24:55.040 --> 00:24:58.640
but it's easy to think of cases or audiences where the reaction might be quite different.

00:25:00.079 --> 00:25:06.319
Here's a graph comparing all-cause mortality in 2020 to the years 2015 to 2019 for the United

00:25:06.319 --> 00:25:12.000
States. If I share this on social media, I guarantee you that someone will yell at me

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:17.599
that I'm being misleading because the y-axis doesn't go to zero. They will demand that it

00:25:17.599 --> 00:25:22.880
should be changed, or they will personally insult me. I guess I should say, and they will

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:28.319
personally insult me. I can guarantee this because it's happened several times. The people who

00:25:28.319 --> 00:25:34.719
complain insist that it should look like this instead. Now, oh, sorry, we went a little too

00:25:34.719 --> 00:25:39.439
far there. Let's go back one. Like this instead. This is worse. It's not wrong, but it's worse.

00:25:40.319 --> 00:25:43.680
There's no reason, there's no real need for the y-axis to go to zero. For one thing,

00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:48.000
the relevant baseline comparison is already in the graph. It's the gray lines that show what's

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:54.239
happening for the five years prior to COVID. And second, there are over 340 million people living

00:25:54.239 --> 00:25:57.439
in the United States, and nobody reasonably thinks that there are weeks when nobody dies.

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:03.680
The thing is, though, you can't do much in the graph itself to make this point to someone who

00:26:03.680 --> 00:26:08.800
is looking at it. Maybe they know and accept the point, maybe they don't. If you have the time,

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:13.119
I suppose you could explain why any kind of iron rule that says the y-axis should go to zero

00:26:13.119 --> 00:26:17.680
would be unreasonable. Now we can look at this. For instance, here's a graph of a long time series

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:22.079
of mean daily global sea surface temperatures with the baseline set to zero degrees Kelvin.

00:26:24.239 --> 00:26:29.680
This was calculated from real data, by the way. Over 17 million spatially weighted observations.

00:26:31.199 --> 00:26:34.800
But you can't explain this personally to everyone who sees your COVID graph, and it probably

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:40.239
wouldn't help to put a note at the bottom either. I do have some sympathy for the people who get

00:26:40.239 --> 00:26:44.000
upset about baselines, because for one thing, at least they're reading the access labels,

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:48.959
and maybe people have, you know, it happens less often than you think, and maybe people have tried

00:26:48.959 --> 00:26:53.839
to put one over on them in the past. But my point is just that there's only so much you can do with

00:26:53.839 --> 00:26:58.959
any particular image to establish your trustworthiness. The design of the graph can't by

00:26:58.959 --> 00:27:09.439
itself do it for you. The real problem, as always, is people. But they're also the solution. It's

00:27:09.439 --> 00:27:16.560
like Homer and beer. The pictures we make are about something. They're made for someone to look

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:21.760
at. So we'd like to know, how much does the person know about the data that we're drawing? How much

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:25.760
do they know about the way that I'm drawing it? Sometimes the only person looking at what you make

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:29.520
is you, but you should still ask that question, because people have a very strong tendency

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:33.040
to go straight to the most complicated thing that they kind of know how to do,

00:27:33.839 --> 00:27:38.079
whether they're drawing a graph or fitting a statistical model. But in any case, someone is

00:27:38.079 --> 00:27:43.680
looking at it. And so there's a relational aspect to any informative visualization. In terms of the

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:48.079
commitments involved, it's a two-sided relation. People may make some demands of you, but if we're

00:27:48.079 --> 00:27:54.400
making a thing, we can also have some expectations. At the level of the graph itself, there's a set

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:58.479
of conventions of representation that your audience needs to understand in order to comprehend the

00:27:58.479 --> 00:28:02.719
graph at all. And as I've said, a lot of the basics of this get handled to a very high standard by

00:28:02.719 --> 00:28:06.560
default in good software, but the people looking at it still have to understand it, and that can

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:10.800
be more challenging than you imagine. So it depends on what you can expect from your audience.

00:28:11.680 --> 00:28:16.560
And beyond that, there's whatever meaning the information you're providing carries for the

00:28:16.560 --> 00:28:22.239
person looking at it. Those expectations that they have, the setting in which they encounter it,

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:26.880
the associations they have with it, usually you have very little control over any of that.

00:28:28.640 --> 00:28:32.479
These days, in fact, one of the decisive features of the social life of images is the way that

00:28:32.479 --> 00:28:37.359
their context can just collapse completely very fast. So last year, I wasn't able to see the total

00:28:37.359 --> 00:28:42.319
eclipse, and the day after it happened, I went to NOAA, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric

00:28:42.319 --> 00:28:46.719
Administration, and downloaded a sequence of images from GOES-East. GOES-East is the

00:28:46.719 --> 00:28:52.319
geostationary satellite that sits over the Earth and is responsible for where US weather maps come

00:28:52.319 --> 00:28:58.000
from. A new GOES-East image gets posted every 10 minutes, and so you can stitch them together

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:04.319
into a little animation. So there's the eclipse from space. It's pretty nice. I posted this on my

00:29:04.319 --> 00:29:09.920
website, and the next day it ended up on the front page of Hacker News. If you don't know what that

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:18.239
is, well, I envy you in the purity of your innocence. So I went and looked at the comments,

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:24.400
which is a rookie mistake, and this was one that jumped out. Now, on the one hand,

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:30.479
leading with, is that animation fake, is a little obnoxious. On the other hand,

00:29:31.119 --> 00:29:36.000
it's kind of a reasonable question to ask of a context-free image. I mean, this person is right.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:40.239
You can see the clouds on the dark side of the Earth in that image if you rerun it, and you

00:29:40.239 --> 00:29:45.439
can't really see the clouds at night from space like this. So what's happening? Well, the camera

00:29:45.439 --> 00:29:50.800
on GOES-East isn't a Kodak Instamatic from 1968 or something. It's an array of image sensors that

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:55.680
look at different parts of the spectrum, and some of those are in the visible part of the light

00:29:55.680 --> 00:29:59.920
range, but other sensors look at cloud coverage via the infrared, and so you do some image

00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:04.239
processing and you get a composite image where you can see both the light and the dark parts at once.

00:30:05.599 --> 00:30:11.760
What commitments have I made to internet randos on Hacker News? Well, to be honest, none.

00:30:13.040 --> 00:30:17.839
I made the image for my own benefit. I put it on my website and left it at that, but then the next

00:30:17.839 --> 00:30:21.839
day when I woke up to my horror and found that it had gotten tens of thousands of views,

00:30:21.839 --> 00:30:27.119
I did add a note explaining the image a little, providing links to the GOES satellite and its

00:30:27.119 --> 00:30:31.760
image feed. So I suppose I did feel that I owed the audience in general, if not a particular

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:37.520
querulous commentator, a bit. But there are limits, sharp limits, I think, to how much more I owe them.

00:30:38.880 --> 00:30:43.359
What's at stake here, I think, in general, is what you might call a social production of trust

00:30:43.359 --> 00:30:47.439
and credibility alongside the organizational and institutional production of data.

00:30:48.319 --> 00:30:53.199
Data visualizations get made and shared. The data comes from somewhere. The image is made by someone

00:30:55.040 --> 00:30:59.760
using some pipeline of software tools. What we want to know is whether that process is reliable

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:04.719
and whether the people behind it are trustworthy. And even though you can partially, I contend,

00:31:05.599 --> 00:31:11.839
institutionalize and formalize many aspects of that process, at its core you can't fully automate it.

00:31:13.680 --> 00:31:20.959
Now don't get me wrong, software can help a lot, especially with reliability. I said earlier that

00:31:20.959 --> 00:31:26.640
reliability and reproducibility were related. Resources like CRAN, tools like PAC and ORANS

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:33.439
and TARGETS can do a tremendous amount to impose order on the unruly business of analysis and

00:31:33.439 --> 00:31:39.920
reporting and visualization pipelines. But even though these tools give us a lot, their creators

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:45.040
don't present them as some sort of panacea. They can't, and they're not meant to, eliminate the need

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:51.680
or automate the process of discovery. They can't, and they're not meant to, eliminate the need for

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:56.079
people who know what they're doing. For one thing, you need some expertise to use these things

00:31:56.079 --> 00:32:00.400
properly. And that's why I think of these issues less in terms of transparency as a sort of abstract

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:05.119
standard, more in terms of webs of relations and ongoing commitments between people who know what

00:32:05.119 --> 00:32:08.560
they're doing. Transparency is no good if you don't know what you're looking at.

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:13.280
A second problem is that once you start working backwards along the causal chain,

00:32:13.280 --> 00:32:19.920
the requirements for full reproducibility and full automation never end. As Carl Sagan remarked,

00:32:19.920 --> 00:32:22.959
to make an apple pie from scratch, first you must create the universe.

00:32:25.199 --> 00:32:29.920
In practice, even when you have a fantastic, fully versioned, cryptographically signed,

00:32:29.920 --> 00:32:34.640
transparently organized build process that can bootstrap and validate an analysis all the way

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:40.400
from the bare metal to figure one, those tools still ground themselves out socially in groups

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:48.880
of real people who know what they're doing and who aren't cheating. Although, recently,

00:32:49.439 --> 00:32:54.800
we've been facing three hard questions, questions that I'll say right away I do not have easy

00:32:54.800 --> 00:32:59.839
answers to. The first is, what happens when people have a thought that goes, hey,

00:33:00.719 --> 00:33:06.400
what if I just made up my data? What if I just pretended to do the thing I said I did?

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:11.680
Our chart men might have been fooling their audiences with their stories of

00:33:11.680 --> 00:33:15.599
pullbacks and head and shoulders and resistance patterns and support levels,

00:33:15.599 --> 00:33:20.400
but at least they were fooling themselves as well. There wasn't anything fraudulent about

00:33:20.400 --> 00:33:24.560
their data either, or about what they did with it. They weren't frauds, they were just wrong.

00:33:25.119 --> 00:33:29.920
That's not the world we live in now. There are very strong temptations, or, as we now politely

00:33:29.920 --> 00:33:35.599
say, incentives, to do the wrong thing. Some of those incentives are just money,

00:33:35.599 --> 00:33:39.760
some of them involve the undeniable attraction of being up on stages like this. It's very nice.

00:33:42.880 --> 00:33:47.760
But not only that, thanks to the very same tools we use to analyze and validate real data,

00:33:47.760 --> 00:33:51.920
it's now easier than ever to generate streams and scores that are plausible looking,

00:33:52.880 --> 00:33:57.680
but fraudulent. As I say, I do not have an easy answer to this, except to say that it's

00:33:57.680 --> 00:34:04.479
a real problem. Science runs on trust, and it is not set up to detect fraud. If you had to check

00:34:04.479 --> 00:34:08.159
fully the authenticity of literally every piece of data that came across your desk,

00:34:08.159 --> 00:34:12.239
every single piece of research, not just whether it was done correctly or in line with your

00:34:12.239 --> 00:34:16.320
standards, but whether the numbers were even real, then everything we do would grind to a halt

00:34:16.320 --> 00:34:22.639
immediately. Most people meet most of their commitments most of the time. They're professionals,

00:34:22.639 --> 00:34:26.320
they believe in what they're doing, and they do the right thing. But the flip side to having

00:34:26.320 --> 00:34:30.479
a system that necessarily runs on trust is that some people take advantage of that trust and

00:34:30.479 --> 00:34:34.800
exploit it. When you do find people who are cheating, you have to punish them.

00:34:36.719 --> 00:34:43.919
The second question goes something like, hey, what if I could just replace all those messy

00:34:43.919 --> 00:34:49.600
and difficult people with a robot? Maybe a robot running on hardware at least as powerful as my

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:54.959
home visualization workstation here. Specifically, what if I could get a large language model

00:34:54.959 --> 00:35:01.679
to read just a tremendous quantity of stuff which I got from somewhere, and then I could ask it

00:35:01.679 --> 00:35:07.199
questions and have it fluently tell me the answer? Or at least have it emit output that the biggest

00:35:07.199 --> 00:35:13.199
matrix you've ever seen in your life says is what an answer probably looks like. Hey, I mean, if not

00:35:13.199 --> 00:35:21.760
answer, why answer-shaped? In the language that I've been using here, LLMs, I'd say, face challenges

00:35:21.760 --> 00:35:26.000
both to reliability and trustworthiness. On the reliability side, when you want to take advantage

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:31.199
of the tremendous leverage they undeniably offer for certain tasks, you have to proceed with a fair

00:35:31.199 --> 00:35:35.280
amount of caution just because of how they work. Everything becomes a measurement problem, which

00:35:35.280 --> 00:35:39.679
we're pretty used to in the world of data analysis. The ways these things can fail, though, can be

00:35:39.679 --> 00:35:43.280
quite unexpected and alien, and we heard about some of those challenges yesterday and how to

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:48.719
address them maybe. Meanwhile, on the trustworthiness side, at least in their current consumer-facing form,

00:35:48.719 --> 00:35:52.800
you have other problems. You may recall an incident from a few months ago when a vibe-coding

00:35:52.800 --> 00:35:57.280
entrepreneur had a bad experience with an AI he was using. At one point, he was so annoyed to

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:02.879
discover that it was faking unit tests that he made it write him an apology letter. And then a bit

00:36:02.879 --> 00:36:09.760
later, when it deleted his production database, the AI explained how it had violated everyone's trust

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:17.600
and was like really totally super sorry. It sounded very sincere, too. Now, I think that asking an AI

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:23.040
to write you an apology letter is a little bit like me finding my alarm clock $20

00:36:23.040 --> 00:36:29.360
when it doesn't wake me up. But you can see how people end up here. LLMs talk to you as if

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:35.120
they were capable of making and abiding by commitments in a way that a person is. They

00:36:35.120 --> 00:36:39.600
very strongly encourage the intentional stance that people are naturally disposed to have,

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:43.679
that disposition to interact with anything that looks like it might be conscious as if it really

00:36:43.679 --> 00:36:50.800
was. What LLMs often find it very hard to do is to say, no, that's not something I can reliably do,

00:36:50.800 --> 00:36:56.560
or I don't know the answer, or actually I should just leave this blank. That is to refuse to take

00:36:56.560 --> 00:37:02.479
on commitments that they can't meet in a way that a trustworthy person would refuse to take

00:37:02.479 --> 00:37:08.560
on commitments that they can't meet. Instead, if a task is nominally within its scope, an LLM will

